00:04:36.550 --> 00:04:40.800
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well thanks again for coming.
"Soul Pancake". I got a chance to breeze through

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:45.280
this a little bit, but, as well as your site.
I'd love to hear your synopsis of what went

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:51.720
into the start of this project and your thoughts
on how successful the site has been so far.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:56.889
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Great. Well, when I started
getting well-known for doing "The Office,"

00:04:56.889 --> 00:05:04.880
I just, I realized that I had a great opportunity
to do something really special and unique

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:08.639
on the web, just because of my celebrity and
stuff.

00:05:08.639 --> 00:05:14.841
And I really thought long and hard and consulted
about it with--. The co-founder of the website,

00:05:14.841 --> 00:05:20.990
soulpancake, is here. Devon, do you want to
stand up? Devon Gundry. Here's here. Stand

00:05:20.990 --> 00:05:22.150
up.

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:23.310
[applause]

00:05:23.310 --> 00:05:32.210
Stand up. And my co-authors are here. I'll
introduce them later. But we just talked about

00:05:32.210 --> 00:05:36.680
things that I was passionate about. And I
really wanted to do something unique and special

00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:39.860
on the web that wasn't there.

00:05:39.860 --> 00:05:43.830
I think that the web has progressed a lot
since we started having these conversations

00:05:43.830 --> 00:05:49.930
about four years ago. But at the time, there
wasn't very much positive on the internet.

00:05:49.930 --> 00:05:57.150
There wasn't very much that was uplifting,
or that was actively working to make the world

00:05:57.150 --> 00:06:01.301
a better place. I mean, granted of course,
there's charity websites and stuff like that.

00:06:01.301 --> 00:06:13.390
But so, the thing that we came up with was
looking at life's big questions because I

00:06:13.390 --> 00:06:17.979
didn't want it to be like, "Oh, I have the
answers," or anything like that. 'Cause I

00:06:17.979 --> 00:06:23.979
don't have the answers. But this is something
that I've been passionate about. I grew up

00:06:23.979 --> 00:06:26.039
in a kind of crazy, Bohemian household.

00:06:26.039 --> 00:06:31.690
And we would have long debates about philosophy
and religion and art and go to galleries and

00:06:31.690 --> 00:06:38.550
museum openings. And the intersection between
art and philosophy and spiritual belief, was

00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:44.450
just always very vibrant in our household.
It was really totally fucked up in every other

00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:51.530
way, but that was a real positive thing that
we had going on. And then I got into school

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:53.180
and continued that interest.

00:06:53.180 --> 00:07:00.020
And I took Great Books classes through high
school. They had a Great Books course in my

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:05.840
high school where we didn't write papers.
We just debated the great authors. And you

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:12.449
were tested on your ability to break down
"Les Miserables" by Victor Hugo and talk about

00:07:12.449 --> 00:07:18.580
the ideas of social justice in there and really
present your case.

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:26.380
And then when I moved on to college and took
philosophy classes. I've also been--. Spirituality

00:07:26.380 --> 00:07:30.370
is an important part of my life and investigating
the world's religions and stuff like that.

00:07:30.370 --> 00:07:34.430
And art has always been an important part
of my life and moving to New York and being

00:07:34.430 --> 00:07:41.620
kind of a crazy Bohemian, doing plays in downtown
theaters and doing weird clown shows off off

00:07:41.620 --> 00:07:43.220
Broadway and stuff like that.

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:49.500
I always was intrigued by all of these things
and how they intersected, because I think

00:07:49.500 --> 00:07:59.560
that in our culture, we're very compartmentalized.
We have our -- you have your work life, here,

00:07:59.560 --> 00:08:03.120
and then maybe outside of your work life you
have your social life. And maybe your friends

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:07.090
are from college or high school, or people
that share hobbies.

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:11.800
And then you have your romantic life and your
family life. And maybe there's a little bit

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:17.211
of a spiritual life here, or maybe there's
your exercise here, or whatever it is that--.

00:08:17.211 --> 00:08:23.940
There are all these different boxes. And I
think that this is a -- there's a lot of great

00:08:23.940 --> 00:08:26.910
things about the modern world. But I think
there's one of the difficulties of the modern

00:08:26.910 --> 00:08:30.389
world is how fractured all of that is.

00:08:30.389 --> 00:08:37.800
And I, personally, believe that it's all really
one and the same thing. We can talk more about

00:08:37.800 --> 00:08:43.320
that later, but, see, I'm talking too much
already. So why we founded it. We just wanted

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:52.350
to build a cool place, to make it cool for
people to talk about what it is to be a human

00:08:52.350 --> 00:08:56.600
being, to continue the discussion that started
really with the ancient Greeks, but it really

00:08:56.600 --> 00:09:04.120
started before them. Just to continue that
same discussion about love and justice and

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:05.570
life and the soul.

00:09:05.570 --> 00:09:11.060
And this is the best way we could think of
to do it was to do the website. And then,

00:09:11.060 --> 00:09:16.350
as soon as we finished our version, our current
version of the website that's up there, we

00:09:16.350 --> 00:09:22.959
moved on to--. We're shooting these webisodes
for the Oprah Winfrey Network. And we did

00:09:22.959 --> 00:09:25.070
this book.

00:09:25.070 --> 00:09:32.270
And we really want Soul Pancake to be a brand,
or a platform, to have a fresh, irreverent,

00:09:32.270 --> 00:09:39.490
unique way of looking at the world and what
it is to be a human being. Does that make

00:09:39.490 --> 00:09:40.490
sense?

00:09:40.490 --> 00:09:44.230
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: It does. It does. And the
structure of the site, for those of you who

00:09:44.230 --> 00:09:48.700
haven't visited it, I recommend it again.
soulpancake.com. The structure of the site

00:09:48.700 --> 00:09:57.410
is very conversational in nature. And so,
there's a lot of banter between commenters.

00:09:57.410 --> 00:10:01.921
So, you post a question--if I'm not mistaken--you
post a question and people just respond as

00:10:01.921 --> 00:10:02.921
they will.

00:10:02.921 --> 00:10:06.820
Some long form, some short form. But then
you have the ability to respond to specific

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:13.660
comments as well. So, as a platform, were
you trying to recreate something similar to

00:10:13.660 --> 00:10:16.920
this class, or what were you going for when
you were actually thinking about the structure

00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:17.920
of Soul Pancake?

00:10:17.920 --> 00:10:22.959
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: I think the--. It was a lot
of guesswork. Like, we just wanted to get

00:10:22.959 --> 00:10:29.380
something up and running. And none of us had
really built a website before with any kind

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:34.709
of traffic. So, we also, besides the-- we
call it the "question collective"--we also

00:10:34.709 --> 00:10:39.720
have challenges on there that we post every
day. There's content.

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:46.330
And a lot of it is about not just talking,
but doing-- creating art and responding with

00:10:46.330 --> 00:10:52.310
visual images and responding with poetry and
not just saying, "Well, I believe that blah,

00:10:52.310 --> 00:10:58.370
blah, blah, blah," you know? That kind of
thing. But yeah. The point was to create a

00:10:58.370 --> 00:11:09.120
community of people that are just searching
and interested in discussing something a little

00:11:09.120 --> 00:11:10.779
bit deeper.

00:11:10.779 --> 00:11:16.649
I found that it just, it had become so--.
It was one of the personal things. It was

00:11:16.649 --> 00:11:25.290
so rare to be able to find people to have
a really deep conversation with. Not a pretentious

00:11:25.290 --> 00:11:33.290
one, but just to--. It isn't done much in
our society. And I think that it should be.

00:11:33.290 --> 00:11:41.140
I think that the rich, soul-filled conversations
need to be part of our daily lives.

00:11:41.140 --> 00:11:47.540
There's nothing to be scared of. But the reason
that we're scared is usually that those discussions

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:52.040
are either people have an agenda, like they
wanna convert you to a way of thinking or

00:11:52.040 --> 00:11:55.360
religious belief, or an atheism belief or
whatever.

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:59.600
But there's an element of like, "I wanna convert
you to how I think". Or else, it's really

00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:05.709
New Age-y and airy fairy and hippie dippie
and lovey dovey in a way that makes me wanna

00:12:05.709 --> 00:12:11.070
vomit. So we just wanted to find something
that was in-between that. And there's a share

00:12:11.070 --> 00:12:15.200
of--. There's New Age hippies on Soul Pancake
and there's also born-again Christians and

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:21.510
born-again Atheists on Soul Pancake. But it's
for everyone.

00:12:21.510 --> 00:12:25.790
And that's the great thing of what we've done.
I would say the single greatest success from

00:12:25.790 --> 00:12:34.170
this version of Soul Pancake is that we have
created something where there are--. There's

00:12:34.170 --> 00:12:45.029
no other website where there's Muslims, Buddhists,
Judists, Christians, and atheists and agnostics,

00:12:45.029 --> 00:12:53.279
all talking civilly to each other in one place.
And that's a really cool thing and a real

00:12:53.279 --> 00:12:54.279
unifying thing.

00:12:54.279 --> 00:12:57.680
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Judists. For those of you
who didn't catch that reference, that's Jewish

00:12:57.680 --> 00:13:03.200
Buddhists, not an interpretation of the Jewish
faith.

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:04.200
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yes, Judists. Exactly.

00:13:04.200 --> 00:13:06.810
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: You made an interesting point,
though, that it's not--. We don't talk about

00:13:06.810 --> 00:13:11.010
these deep subjects as much either in current
society. I have a hard time believing it was

00:13:11.010 --> 00:13:13.120
ever really done that frequently.

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:17.983
But I mean, do you feel like there is something
about the nature of the internet, or maybe

00:13:17.983 --> 00:13:22.220
about your site specifically, that allows
people to talk about these. Or, do you think

00:13:22.220 --> 00:13:26.570
most people would be willing to talk about
them if only these subjects came up more often?

00:13:26.570 --> 00:13:33.130
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: You know, I think it's a little
all of the above. I think that—yeah, I think

00:13:33.130 --> 00:13:42.290
that – [pause]. I don't know. It's easy
to just get, it's easy to get doors shut in

00:13:42.290 --> 00:13:50.250
your face if you wanna talk about them, I
think. And I don't know. I don't know why

00:13:50.250 --> 00:13:52.329
that is. I don't know why that is exactly.

00:13:52.329 --> 00:13:55.970
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Do you find yourself bringing
up these kinds of subjects? I mean, these

00:13:55.970 --> 00:14:00.389
are fairly, not just thought-provoking questions,
but they're very like blisteringly honest

00:14:00.389 --> 00:14:05.170
questions where you have to be true to your
own beliefs to really have a good conversation

00:14:05.170 --> 00:14:06.170
about them.

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:07.170
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yeah.

00:14:07.170 --> 00:14:08.170
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Do you find [ ]?

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:10.110
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yeah, I do. I do all the time
and it clears the room like a mo-fo.

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:11.110
[laughter]

00:14:11.110 --> 00:14:19.769
It's crazy. Like, you bring up just the big
question, "Do you believe in God?" And people

00:14:19.769 --> 00:14:26.260
are like, "Uh-oh. Here it comes." And then
they're like, "No," or, "Yes." Or whatever.

00:14:26.260 --> 00:14:27.850
"Why? How do you believe that?"

00:14:27.850 --> 00:14:31.000
Or, "What do you think's gonna happen when
you die? Really? Do you think that just your

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.930
body starts to decay? That's it? No more consciousness?
That's what happens?" "Yes," or, "no," or,

00:14:35.930 --> 00:14:45.470
"I don't know." Or whatever, but I think that
Thoreau--. I think that Soul Pancake is really

00:14:45.470 --> 00:14:46.880
inspired by the transcendentalists.

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:50.829
And one of the things I realized in writing
this book is like, "Wow, I really came back

00:14:50.829 --> 00:14:53.779
around." Like, oh yeah, I used to read all
those transcendentalists in high school. I

00:14:53.779 --> 00:14:55.209
was like, "I really am a transcendentalist."

00:14:55.209 --> 00:15:01.290
I believe that art and spirituality and the
expression of being human is -- transcends

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:09.339
just our normal pooping and fucking and shitting
and eating lives that we all live, that we're

00:15:09.339 --> 00:15:12.300
longing for something more and something deeper.

00:15:12.300 --> 00:15:17.130
And Thoreau said. 'The unexamined life is
not worth living' and it's just about examining

00:15:17.130 --> 00:15:22.779
our lives a little bit, a little bit deeper,
just to get "Who are you? Who are we? What

00:15:22.779 --> 00:15:29.490
do I stand for? Where's my integrity? What's
my legacy? What is my relationship to the

00:15:29.490 --> 00:15:35.610
earth and to other people and to a higher
being, or to nature?" Whatever it is.

00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:41.130
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: The Thoreau quote, "The unexamined
life," that definitely came to mind when I

00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:44.850
was looking at this. And the feeling that
I've always gotten--. I was growing up, I've

00:15:44.850 --> 00:15:49.330
always wanted to have conversations, found
it as difficult, is that it's--

00:15:49.330 --> 00:15:50.510
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: You can talk to me, Jesse.

00:15:50.510 --> 00:15:51.510
[laughter]

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:53.880
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: it's really difficult. It's
really difficult to examine, right? You have

00:15:53.880 --> 00:15:57.160
to be honest and you often realize is this
disconnect between what you'd like to think

00:15:57.160 --> 00:16:01.759
you believe and what you actually do. And
so, these conversations get, like I said,

00:16:01.759 --> 00:16:04.639
very honest and sometimes depressingly so.

00:16:04.639 --> 00:16:09.759
Do you feel like that your site is an effective
conduit, though, for people to be honest,

00:16:09.759 --> 00:16:12.560
or they constantly putting out there what
they think they'd like to believe?

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:16.950
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: You know, it's a lot of it
is -- we'd like to do a lot more with the

00:16:16.950 --> 00:16:22.370
site than what's up there, to be really honest
with you guys. I think it's a good start.

00:16:22.370 --> 00:16:28.730
And we need funding and we need a development
team and we need a lot of things to be able--

00:16:28.730 --> 00:16:31.180
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Wink.

00:16:31.180 --> 00:16:34.600
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: to do that.

00:16:34.600 --> 00:16:35.600
[laughter]

00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:37.329
But, Larry, Sergey.

00:16:37.329 --> 00:16:38.329
[laughter]

00:16:38.329 --> 00:16:43.920
But I think that, yeah. I think it's a good
start towards that. I think ultimately, a

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:49.550
bunch of anonymous people saying, "Well I
think blah, blah, blah," is not necessarily

00:16:49.550 --> 00:16:50.750
the best way to go about it.

00:16:50.750 --> 00:16:57.670
And sometimes, the site devolves into that.
And we're figuring out a lot of other ways

00:16:57.670 --> 00:17:02.510
that we wanna really, especially, bring the
arts into the site, and creativity and have

00:17:02.510 --> 00:17:11.720
the people be able to have more artistic challenges
and people to post videos and express themselves

00:17:11.720 --> 00:17:16.880
beyond just text writing and saying, "Well
I think this, that, and the other thing."

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:22.430
So, it's partially successful, I would say.
It's a good stab at it. And I think it's really

00:17:22.430 --> 00:17:28.010
the only place on the web that is trying to
do that. I think there's not really much to

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:35.290
compare it to. I think that belief.net may
be, but that's a really fractured thing. If

00:17:35.290 --> 00:17:38.520
you're a Buddhist, you go to this page of
belief.net. And if you're a Christian, you

00:17:38.520 --> 00:17:39.520
go here.

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:44.679
And if you're Catholic, you go here. And you
know what I mean? It's all very fractured.

00:17:44.679 --> 00:17:49.130
We're trying to just bring people together.
It's about the human experience. It's not

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:51.120
about your little belief box.

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:56.150
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: I really like the idea of
engaging your visitors. I'd like to ask about

00:17:56.150 --> 00:18:00.309
how much response you feel like you've had
to when you put out these challenges? But

00:18:00.309 --> 00:18:04.350
certainly, in this book, you've challenged
your readers to do things.

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:08.890
One of the things you challenge to do often
is create lists, these pros and cons lists.

00:18:08.890 --> 00:18:12.789
And this has happened over and over and over
again in the book. Could you give me five

00:18:12.789 --> 00:18:16.620
reasons why you think lists are a good idea,
or is there a specific reason why you've chosen

00:18:16.620 --> 00:18:18.410
that approach? It seems to be pretty common.

00:18:18.410 --> 00:18:23.260
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Lists, we do it a lot on the
site and we did a lot in the book. We do "list

00:18:23.260 --> 00:18:28.179
the five things that you blah, blah, blah."
Or, 'write down the three things," or "the

00:18:28.179 --> 00:18:30.510
ten most important things," or something like
that.

00:18:30.510 --> 00:18:35.340
And I think it's just an easy way to get the
conversation going. I don't think the lists

00:18:35.340 --> 00:18:42.140
are the be-all and the end-all. I think that
lists make it--. It's just an easier way to

00:18:42.140 --> 00:18:44.390
just start that conversation.

00:18:44.390 --> 00:18:49.520
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: And when you start that conversation
the harder way, which is create art, do poetry,

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:51.080
paint a picture or something like that--

00:18:51.080 --> 00:18:52.080
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yeah.

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:53.160
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: do you feel like you've had
a good response from your community? Or has

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:54.160
it been pretty tough to get that going?

00:18:54.160 --> 00:18:58.260
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Oh, very much so. I mean,
we have--. You guys can help me more with

00:18:58.260 --> 00:19:06.500
the content stuff that we've done, but we've
had such incredible artistic challenges. What

00:19:06.500 --> 00:19:10.789
are some of the ones that you think that have
been really good with like, people sharing

00:19:10.789 --> 00:19:13.640
their art specifically for Soul Pancake that
they've created?

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:18.330
&gt;&gt;Woman #1: Photos are nice. We did a photo
on capturing light that reflects your soul

00:19:18.330 --> 00:19:20.380
and that got a ton of photos.

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:25.560
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Like a photo challenge that
capture light with a camera that reflects

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:32.419
your soul and get hundreds of responses. I
mean, it's a really beautiful gallery when

00:19:32.419 --> 00:19:33.419
it's done.

00:19:33.419 --> 00:19:34.970
&gt;&gt;Woman #1: We did a Haiku on--

00:19:34.970 --> 00:19:36.270
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Haiku's are always good.

00:19:36.270 --> 00:19:42.209
&gt;&gt;Woman: We did a Haiku on [ ] what things
can happen when you die.

00:19:42.209 --> 00:19:45.610
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Haiku and what you think happens
to you when you die. That kind of thing. So

00:19:45.610 --> 00:19:49.220
those artistic social interactions.

00:19:49.220 --> 00:19:50.310
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Haiku's are particularly
nice--

00:19:50.310 --> 00:19:51.310
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yeah.

00:19:51.310 --> 00:19:53.240
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: because they're short, fairly
non-committal. You can get someone to write

00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:54.240
something like that--.

00:19:54.240 --> 00:20:00.520
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yeah, you can dash one off,
but then you start to dash it off and then

00:20:00.520 --> 00:20:05.200
you go, "Oh, this is trickier than it seems."
And you start to retool it and retool it and

00:20:05.200 --> 00:20:10.539
strip it away and pare it down and think about
it and find the right word. And it's interesting

00:20:10.539 --> 00:20:13.580
'cause it's like a little Rubik's cube.

00:20:13.580 --> 00:20:18.040
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well, yeah. But it has a
really great hook for engagement. So, have

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:22.950
you found other ways to--. I mean when you
present something like "paint a picture" or

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:27.991
"do something large-scale" that expresses
X, Y, Z, again, you're gonna weed out a lot

00:20:27.991 --> 00:20:29.510
of people just because of the amount of effort.

00:20:29.510 --> 00:20:33.790
Have you found ways to almost trick people
into getting to think more deeply, which I

00:20:33.790 --> 00:20:35.230
find is probably the best way to get these
conversations started, is don't let them know

00:20:35.230 --> 00:20:37.730
that you're getting the conversation started.

00:20:37.730 --> 00:20:42.360
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Well, I think--. And that's
what the whole thing of Soul Pancake and with

00:20:42.360 --> 00:20:46.510
our content is. And a little bit of what we
do in the book is exactly what you're talking

00:20:46.510 --> 00:20:49.760
about. It's like, tricking people into ways
of getting the conversation started.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:54.300
And I think that's what we do. I think that's
what lists do. I think that's what Haikus

00:20:54.300 --> 00:20:59.700
do. I think that if something is really simple
like, what's the most, what's the happiest

00:20:59.700 --> 00:21:03.809
you've ever been, or something like that.
People can go, "Oh, that's this. It's that."

00:21:03.809 --> 00:21:08.510
It's easy, but it gets you putting yourself
out there and engaging in them, in the mush.

00:21:08.510 --> 00:21:14.080
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: You take that into what is
real happiness and all of a sudden, next thing

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:15.080
you know, you're quoting more and--.

00:21:15.080 --> 00:21:16.080
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: There you go.

00:21:16.080 --> 00:21:17.200
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: It's great people.

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:18.200
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yeah.

00:21:18.200 --> 00:21:23.471
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well, I find, I found a lot
of the comments rather fascinating on some,

00:21:23.471 --> 00:21:27.929
at least the more recent conversations. I
didn't go tremendously far back. But do you,

00:21:27.929 --> 00:21:29.770
or your team, ever read through the comments?

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:35.390
Do you ever comment yourself? I know it's
a loaded question I'm asking, but do you ever

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:36.390
join that discussion, or at least monitor
it?

00:21:36.390 --> 00:21:41.190
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: I do, sometimes. But I read
the site every day. And I read the--. I get

00:21:41.190 --> 00:21:46.210
up and I check it and I read what the challenges
are and look at the responses and stuff like

00:21:46.210 --> 00:21:52.590
that. I don't read every single one, but I
like to see where it's going and where it

00:21:52.590 --> 00:21:54.860
needs to be going and stuff like that.

00:21:54.860 --> 00:22:01.049
So, I'm very engaged in it. I just think it's
like a dream come true. It's really cool that

00:22:01.049 --> 00:22:07.580
there's teenagers from Dubuque, and there's
college students in Namibia and there's born-again

00:22:07.580 --> 00:22:16.000
Christians in Athens, Georgia. And they're
all just digging into the stuff of life and

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:20.860
into the intersection of creativity and spirituality
and philosophy.

00:22:20.860 --> 00:22:25.591
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well I find it very genuine,
too. It's not, to be honest--

00:22:25.591 --> 00:22:26.591
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Right.

00:22:26.591 --> 00:22:27.591
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: with something like--

00:22:27.591 --> 00:22:28.591
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: I find you very genuine.

00:22:28.591 --> 00:22:29.591
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Oh, well. You know, it's
because I mean it. It's because I care.

00:22:29.591 --> 00:22:30.591
[laughter]

00:22:30.591 --> 00:22:34.020
That's what it's about. But with something
like this, you could easily expect it to go

00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:40.039
into what's known as a flame war, or where
the comments just become inane. If you look

00:22:40.039 --> 00:22:45.610
at the comments of a lot of very popular social
sites, they just get ignorant or racist or

00:22:45.610 --> 00:22:46.740
just extremely hyperbolic.

00:22:46.740 --> 00:22:50.740
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: The people that use Soul Pancake
regularly and it's not a ton of them, but

00:22:50.740 --> 00:22:59.720
however 20 thousand people that congregate
there, they are very protective of the site.

00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:01.659
And they really don't like trolling.

00:23:01.659 --> 00:23:08.830
And they really don't like assholes just posting
stuff. And they'll kick 'em out. They'll flag

00:23:08.830 --> 00:23:14.860
them and get rid of them. They're very--.
They really want it to be a special place.

00:23:14.860 --> 00:23:20.200
You see that a lot in the comments. And that's
another very successful thing about it.

00:23:20.200 --> 00:23:25.809
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: When I signed up for an account,
it was fairly non-invasive. There wasn't a

00:23:25.809 --> 00:23:30.970
lot that you were asking from me. But you
also -- so which again, made the cost of entry

00:23:30.970 --> 00:23:36.400
very low. But do you monitor at all the, or
do you have a sense of the demographics that

00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:38.110
play around this site? Do you have a sense
of who your audience is composed of?

00:23:38.110 --> 00:23:39.919
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Oh, we track every user.

00:23:39.919 --> 00:23:42.980
[laughter]

00:23:42.980 --> 00:23:52.530
We know everything. We know their buying habits.
We know how often they defecate, their regularity.

00:23:52.530 --> 00:23:54.380
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: You follow their Twitter
feed, is what you're saying.

00:23:54.380 --> 00:23:55.530
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Yes.

00:23:55.530 --> 00:23:56.690
[Rainn Wilson laughs]

00:23:56.690 --> 00:23:57.730
Very good. Boom.

00:23:57.730 --> 00:23:58.730
[laughter]

00:23:58.730 --> 00:24:03.610
I'm doing Twitter tomorrow. Any messages you
want me to pass on to the folks over at Twitter?

00:24:03.610 --> 00:24:05.010
[pause]

00:24:05.010 --> 00:24:06.410
[laughter]

00:24:06.410 --> 00:24:07.970
Get a life? What? Anything?

00:24:07.970 --> 00:24:09.020
[laughter]

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:11.590
Your site will be obsolete in three years.

00:24:11.590 --> 00:24:12.679
[laughter]

00:24:12.679 --> 00:24:13.679
And ours won't.

00:24:13.679 --> 00:24:16.640
[laughter]

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:23.280
Anything? Umm, umm no. What was the question?
I don't know.

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:26.710
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well, I mean do you monitor
the demographics, the profiles, the types

00:24:26.710 --> 00:24:28.050
of people, where they're coming from?

00:24:28.050 --> 00:24:32.770
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: No. We haven't. We may. We're
trying to get some funding. So, that's gonna

00:24:32.770 --> 00:24:37.730
require us to figure out the ages and demographics
of who's using the site regularly and stuff

00:24:37.730 --> 00:24:40.880
like that. So, but we haven't to this point.
No.

00:24:40.880 --> 00:24:43.870
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well, there's not any advertising
on the site now, is there?

00:24:43.870 --> 00:24:44.870
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: There's not. No.

00:24:44.870 --> 00:24:48.160
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: So, would you ever consider
this a profit, a profitable venture? I thought

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:49.590
it was more of a non-profit--.

00:24:49.590 --> 00:24:53.929
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: It is not--. It is a for-profit
venture with a non-profit heart.

00:24:53.929 --> 00:24:54.929
[laughter]

00:24:54.929 --> 00:24:55.929
And uh--.

00:24:55.929 --> 00:24:56.929
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: The best of intentions.

00:24:56.929 --> 00:24:58.710
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: But we haven't figured out
how to make any money off of it yet.

00:24:58.710 --> 00:24:59.710
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: That's fair.

00:24:59.710 --> 00:25:02.140
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: But the book is doing well.
The book was in the New York Times bestseller

00:25:02.140 --> 00:25:05.610
list for the last six weeks. So, that's been
pretty cool. And--.

00:25:05.610 --> 00:25:06.610
[applause]

00:25:06.610 --> 00:25:12.730
Yeah. Yeah. New York Times bestselling author.
What?

00:25:12.730 --> 00:25:14.169
[laughter]

00:25:14.169 --> 00:25:17.410
Who are those people on that TV screen having
a conference room meeting?

00:25:17.410 --> 00:25:18.570
[laughter]

00:25:18.570 --> 00:25:19.570
Who are those people?

00:25:19.570 --> 00:25:23.340
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: It's a bit magical. We have,
literally, people all around the world.

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:25.240
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Wait. Now they're waving at
me. How are you hearing?

00:25:25.240 --> 00:25:26.890
[laughter]

00:25:26.890 --> 00:25:29.710
But they're talking to each other like they're
having a meeting. Who are those people?

00:25:29.710 --> 00:25:32.010
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: They're definitely talking
about you. That's for sure. They're actually

00:25:32.010 --> 00:25:35.159
in San Francisco. So, we have video-conferencing
abilities to bring in--.

00:25:35.159 --> 00:25:37.320
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Why don't they come out here?
Why are they in San Francisco?

00:25:37.320 --> 00:25:40.630
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well, you know, it's a packed
house. We wouldn't wanna make this a little

00:25:40.630 --> 00:25:45.770
bit too crowded. It's already getting warm
in here. They would only add to it, really.

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:48.230
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: How you doing? You in the
striped shirt. What's your name?

00:25:48.230 --> 00:25:49.230
[laughter]

00:25:49.230 --> 00:25:51.460
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: They're good people.

00:25:51.460 --> 00:25:53.620
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: I'm serious.

00:25:53.620 --> 00:25:55.280
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: They're good people.

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:56.690
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: OK. They're good people?

00:25:56.690 --> 00:25:58.460
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: You can trust them.

00:25:58.460 --> 00:26:00.230
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: I don't like them.

00:26:00.230 --> 00:26:02.600
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Well, I don't know about
that.

00:26:02.600 --> 00:26:03.600
[laughter]

00:26:03.600 --> 00:26:06.360
Well, in any case, [laughter] the book is
doing well. The book is doing well. It's [ ].

00:26:06.360 --> 00:26:09.549
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: The book is doing well. So
we made a little coin off the book. And now

00:26:09.549 --> 00:26:15.440
we're doing these Oprah webisodes, which some
day we hope to turn Soul Pancake into a little

00:26:15.440 --> 00:26:17.771
bit more of a TV format as well.

00:26:17.771 --> 00:26:25.110
So, it can be books. We've even talked about
like a Soul Pancake music label, supporting

00:26:25.110 --> 00:26:32.650
artists that just share our vision. And that
doesn't mean like, wimpy--. I'm not talking

00:26:32.650 --> 00:26:36.450
about Sarah McLachlan kind of music. I mean,
to me--.

00:26:36.450 --> 00:26:37.450
[laughter]

00:26:37.450 --> 00:26:39.330
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Nothing against Miss McLachlan,
I'm sure.

00:26:39.330 --> 00:26:41.260
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: Is she here, or what?

00:26:41.260 --> 00:26:42.260
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Great.

00:26:42.260 --> 00:26:51.409
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: She'd kick my ass. But nothing--.
Well, 'cause to me, the most spiritually and

00:26:51.409 --> 00:26:57.559
philosophically uplifting music in my mind
is Radiohead, or Sigur Ros. You know what

00:26:57.559 --> 00:27:00.480
I mean? There's people that can be making
music about--. And that's what I think is

00:27:00.480 --> 00:27:04.260
so interesting about the arts is that, what
was I just talking? This is way off topic,

00:27:04.260 --> 00:27:05.929
but I'm gonna say something interesting.

00:27:05.929 --> 00:27:08.299
[laughter]

00:27:08.299 --> 00:27:10.970
Write this down. Where you going?

00:27:10.970 --> 00:27:11.970
[laughter]

00:27:11.970 --> 00:27:12.970
Seriously.

00:27:12.970 --> 00:27:13.970
[laughter]

00:27:13.970 --> 00:27:20.610
What did she say? All right. Get outta here.
Go on.

00:27:20.610 --> 00:27:21.610
[laughter]

00:27:21.610 --> 00:27:23.490
It's a stupid scarf.

00:27:23.490 --> 00:27:24.490
[laughter]

00:27:24.490 --> 00:27:26.590
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: Ooh.

00:27:26.590 --> 00:27:36.531
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: I am the Don Rickles of authors.
The, what was I saying? Oh.

00:27:36.531 --> 00:27:37.820
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: I think of a label.

00:27:37.820 --> 00:27:43.650
&gt;&gt;Rainn Wilson: There's an interesting theater
game that I used to play back in theater school

00:27:43.650 --> 00:27:48.440
and doing improv and stuff like that. And
it was where you would, it's a fascinating

00:27:48.440 --> 00:27:51.900
thing. You guys should do it when you're doing
like you're group mime classes down in the

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:53.080
courtyard, or whatever you do here.

00:27:53.080 --> 00:27:55.740
[laughter]

00:27:55.740 --> 00:28:00.470
You, everyone writes down an emotion and you
stick the emotion in a hat. And then, every

00:28:00.470 --> 00:28:04.740
group of like three or four people picks an
emotion out of the hat. And then that's the

00:28:04.740 --> 00:28:11.020
emotion that they need to try and make the
audience feel. So you come up with a scene

00:28:11.020 --> 00:28:13.980
to make the audience feel that emotion.

00:28:13.980 --> 00:28:18.490
And it's really interesting because if it's
like, anger, it's like, how do you do a scene

00:28:18.490 --> 00:28:23.390
in front of people to make them feel angry?
Like, you do an angry scene, you might get

00:28:23.390 --> 00:28:28.299
laughs. And it might actually be really entertaining.
'Cause at the end, you say, "What did you

00:28:28.299 --> 00:28:29.940
guys feel? What did you actually feel?

00:28:29.940 --> 00:28:35.470
Not what did you think you were supposed to
feel, but what did you actually feel?" And

00:28:35.470 --> 00:28:40.880
it's fascinating. 'Cause the anger one, like
there was a famous scene that was done when

00:28:40.880 --> 00:28:46.160
I was in school, where people pretended to
be like these sweet, little, old ladies who

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:49.470
started using the "n" word all the time. And
it was just like--.

00:28:49.470 --> 00:28:55.020
And I mean, people were just outraged, but
it really worked. It really made them feel

00:28:55.020 --> 00:29:01.380
anger, but it's interesting how that works.
And you can also make people feel angry by

00:29:01.380 --> 00:29:07.270
boring them. So, just doing a really bad scene
can really make people feel angry.

00:29:07.270 --> 00:29:08.270
[laughter]

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:13.120
But it's interesting because we talk about
like, what is art that inspires, or what is

00:29:13.120 --> 00:29:21.419
art that uplifts, that makes you feel connected,
that it feels like soul-enriching. 'Cause

00:29:21.419 --> 00:29:28.850
a lot of times for me, that's stuff that the
artist, that was not their intention. It's

00:29:28.850 --> 00:29:32.120
not what they set out to do.

00:29:32.120 --> 00:29:39.630
Radiohead sets out to write these weird, jarring
soundscapes that all are about human alienation.

00:29:39.630 --> 00:29:49.799
But nothing makes me feel more like, euphoric
and connected and loving and just transported

00:29:49.799 --> 00:29:54.429
and transcendent than their music. You know
what I mean? So it's an odd thing. So that's

00:29:54.429 --> 00:29:58.580
just a little interesting thing. Wasn't that
interesting? OK.

00:29:58.580 --> 00:30:02.549
&gt;&gt;Jesse Nichols: [laughs] Something that--.
